In Python, you can use the render_template_string function to render templates from strings. You can inject variables into these templates with the {{ }} syntax.

Here's an example of using render_template_string to create a page with a dynamic greeting:

```py
from flask import Flask, render_template_string

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def home():
    user = "Bob"
    return render_template_string('Hello, {{ user }}. Welcome to {{ site }}!')
```

To inject HTML, you can use the {{}} syntax directly. Here's an example:

```py
@app.route('/search')
def search():
    results = "Bob"
    return render_template_string('<div>{{ results }} search results found</div>')

```
To inject arbitrary HTML into a template, you can use the {{}} syntax directly. Here's an example:

```py
@app.route('/results')
def results():
    results = "<em>Bob</em>"
    return render_template_string('<div>{{ results }}</div>')
```
Injecting user input into templates can be dangerous if you're not careful. To prevent XSS attacks, make sure to use the |safe filter on any variables that contain HTML. Here's an example:

```py
@app.route('/user/<name>')
def user(name):
    return render_template_string('<div>Hello, {{ name | safe }}</div>')

```
In this example, the |safe filter is used to prevent XSS attacks when rendering user input. Without it, the name variable would be automatically escaped to prevent attacks.

